title: Andrew Jackson's Sword and Scabbard
creator: Unknown
description: Andrew Jackson carried this sword and scabbard while commanding the American forces, during the Creek War and in the War of 1812.

title: Twice captured Presentation Sword
creator: Hunt & Goodwin. and W. Clauberg
description: Presentation Sword given to a calverly verteran. The Sword is engraved and made of still with a brass hilt, as well as a metal scabard.

title: Congressional Presentation Sword and Scabbard of Major General John E. Wool
creator: Samuel Jackson
description: This sword was awarded by the United States Congress to General Wool in 1854 in belated recognition of his pivotal role in the American victory at Buena Vista (February 1847) during the Mexican War
subject: Swords
source: The MET muesum.Link

title: Schuyler, Hartley & Graham Presentation Sword, Ames Manufacturing Co. Scabbard Inscribed "Genl. U.S. Grant Galena Ill's, Presented by G.W. Graham, C.B. Lagow, C.C. Marsh & John Cook 1861"
creator: Schuyler, Hartley & Graham and Ames Manufacturing Company
description: An incredibly complex presentation sword given to Ulysses S. Grant in April 1862. It has designs depicting multiple aspects of the United States, the military, and Greek Gods.
subject: Edged-Weapons; Civil War
source: National Museum of American History, Smithsonian. Link

title: Ames Manufacturing Co. Presentation Sword
creator: Ames Manufacturing Company
description: A straight Sword with a silver chasing and floral spiraling. Scabbard is inscribed with "Presented to Col. John R Brooke 1862".

title: Hunting Sword of Prince Camillo Borghese (1775–1832)
creator: François Pirmet (French, Paris, recorded 1779–1818)
description: Hunting sword owned by Napoléon's brother in law with gold decorations on the gaurd
subject: Swords-Hunting
source: The Met museum.Link

title: Congressional Presentation Sword and Scabbard of Peleg K. Dunham (1794–1822)
creator: William Rose Sr
description: One of the finest surviving sword from a commission by congress during the War of 1812. The sword was presented to midshipman Peleg K. Dunham, a nineteen-year-old serving on the USS Caledonia during the Battle of Lake Erie
subject: Swords; Arms; Edged-Weapons
source: The Met museum. Link

title: Presentation Sword Honoring Commandant Jean-Baptiste Marchand (1863–1934) for His Conduct at Fashoda
creator: Hilt designed by Jean-Joseph-Marie-Anatole Marquet de Vasselot. Blade designer not listed
description: The hilt was designed by the sculptor Anatole Marquet de Vasselot for a sword that the daily newspaper La Patrie wished to award to the French military officer Jean-Baptiste Marchand. The sword was intended to honor the spirit, abnegation, and competence that Marchand had shown in Africa as the leader of a small expeditionary force known as the Congo-Nile Mission.
subject: Swords; Arms; Edged-Weapons
source: The Met Museum.Link

title: Sword with Scabbard of Faustin I (1782–1867), Emperor of Haiti
creator: Robert Mole
description: This lavish ceremonial sword was made for Faustin-Élie Soulouque, who ruled Haiti as Emperor Faustin I from 1849 to 1859. It was presented to him by The Grand Masonic Lodge of Haiti in 1850.
subject: Swords; Arms; Edged-Weapons
source: The Met Museum. Link

title: Smallsword Presented by the City of Paris to Commandant Ildefonse Favé (1812–1894)
creator: Paul Bled
description: Small Sword given to the city of Paris to commemorate the brith of Prince Napoleon. Sometime after the announcement of the brith, this sword was commissioned from Lepage-Moutier, a renowned firm of Parisian gunmakers.
subject: Swords; Arms; Edged-Weapons
source: The Met museum. Link

title: Hunting sword
creator: Emanuel Pioté and Jacob H. Köchert
description: This incredibly intracate hunting sword and scabbard was made for one of the counts Hoyos-Sprinzenstein. The scabbard locket is inscribed "Pioté et Köchert," the leading Viennese jewelers of the nineteenth century.
subject: Swords; Arms; Edged-Weapons; Swords-Hunting
source: The Met museum.Link

title: Toledo 1873 Presentation Sword
creator: Unknown
description: The blade of this presentation sword is slightly curved and single-edged. Both sides are decorated in silver, gold, and blue chasing. On the obverse, there are silver scroll designs and floral sprays on a gold background, and a list of Grant's Civil War battles cast in gold writing on a black banner.
subject: Edged-Weapons
source: National Muesum of American History, Smithsonian. Link

title: Presentation Sword, Inscribed "Major General E.W. Ripley U.S. Army"
creator: Unknown
description: Long, straight single edged presentation sword and scabbard give to E.W. Ripley following the War of 1812. "Major General E.W. Ripley U.S. Army is engraved on the scabbard.
subject: Edged-Weapons
source: National Muesum of American History, Smithsonian. Link

title: Sword Voted to Ulysses S. Grant at the Metropolitan Fair
creator: Tiffany & Co
description: This sword was voted to Ulysses S. Grant at the Metropolitan Fair in aid of the United States Sanitary Commission in New York, New York on April 23, 1864. The United States Sanitary Commission was a private relief organization that supported army hospitals and sick and wounded soldiers during the Civil War.
subject: Edged Weapons; Presentation
source: National Muesum of American History, Smithsonian. Link

title: Saber Bayonet for the Confederate Cook & Brother Rifle
creator: Cook and Brother
description: This saber bayonet was made for use on the Confederate Cook & Brother rifle. The hilt is marked "SUNFLOWERGUARD." The Sunflower Guards were Company I of the 21st Mississippi Infantry Regiment. The company was raised in Sunflower County, Mississippi.
